        "number": 3,
        "title": "Military victory and three-year tribute — faithfulness confirmed in the visible world",
        "range": "27:5",
        "excerpt": "He fought also with the king of the Ammonites and prevailed over them so that the Ammonites gave him during that year one hundred talents of silver, ten thousand kors of wheat and ten thousand of barley.",
        "body": "The Ammonite campaign is reported in a single verse, yet it carries significant theological and historical weight. The Ammonites — descendants of Lot (Genesis 19:38), occupying Transjordan east of the Jordan River — were persistent rivals of Israel and Judah throughout the monarchy. Their subjugation under Jotham confirms that his reign was not merely stable internally but actively dominant externally. The tribute is substantial: one hundred talents of silver was approximately 3.75 tons — a figure comparable to the tribute exacted by Solomon (1 Kings 10:14) and later demanded by Assyria from Israel (2 Kings 15:19). Ten thousand kors each of wheat and barley (roughly 58,000 bushels each) represented enormous agricultural production. The Chronicler includes these numbers not to impress with military economics but to document the material blessing that accompanied faithful kingship.\n\nThe three-year duration of the tribute (the second and third years repeated the first year's payment) is especially important. A single-year tribute could be a one-off concession; three consecutive years of equal tribute confirms sustained Judean dominance over Ammon. The Chronicler's retributive theology is precise: sustained faithfulness produces sustained outcomes. This is not a lucky victory but a documented pattern. The verb chazaq ('prevailed over them,' v.5) is the same root that will be used in the theological summary of verse 6 ('Jotham became mighty'). The Chronicler places both occurrences in immediate sequence so the reader cannot miss the connection: military strength (v.5) is an instance of the broader God-given might (v.6).\n\nThe parallel account in 2 Kings 15:37 mentions that during Jotham's days the LORD began sending Rezin of Syria and Pekah of Israel against Judah — the beginning of the Syro-Ephraimite crisis that would dominate the reign of Ahaz. The Chronicler omits this detail from chapter 27, preserving the Ammonite victory as the chapter's military centerpiece and deferring the Assyrian shadow to the Ahaz narrative. This editorial selectivity is not dishonesty — it is purposeful focus on what Jotham's reign distinctively achieved.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Lacham* (waged war, v.5) — the standard military engagement verb. *Chazaq* (prevailed, v.5; grew powerful, v.6) — the deliberate double use links military outcome to theological cause. *Kikkar* (talent of silver) — approximately 75 pounds per talent; 100 talents = approximately 3.75 tons of silver."
